[2] India (Diarrhea)
Date: Wed, 13 Aug 2003 10:14:34 +0100
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@ntlworld.com>
Source: The Australian, August 13, 2003 (edited)
<http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5744,6943728%255E1702,00.html>

Diarrhea outbreak kills 67
--------------------------
An outbreak of diarrhea in India's most populous state has killed at least
67 people, mostly children, in the past 10 days, a government health
official said on Wed 13 Aug 2003.
Deaths from waterborne diseases during the rainy season are common in Uttar
Pradesh, an impoverished state with poor water, power and health
facilities. An outbreak of diarrhea has been reported in 11 districts and
more than 250 people have been admitted to hospitals statewide, said RB
Singh, the officer in charge of epidemic control. At least 67 people have
died since 4 Aug 2003, he said, most of them children.
Local news reports say the death toll is much higher than the official
figure. Worst affected has been the district of Ballia, 320 kilometers east
of Lucknow, the state capital, where at least 19 children have died in the
past 5 days, said Dr SR Yadav, the district's chief medical officer. 6
children died of diarrhea last week in Lucknow, where sewage entered a
pipeline carrying drinking water to the Jankipuram neighborhood. "We were
getting brownish colored water. Complaints were lodged ... but nothing
happened," said a resident of Jankipuram said. "The government woke up only
after children started dying." Another Jankipuram resident said he was
forced to take his 3 year old son to a government hospital as private
clinics were overcrowded with patients. "He died before doctors could
attend to him," the man said with tears in his eyes.
Uttar Pradesh Health Minister Aridaman Singh said the government is keeping
a close watch on the situation. Health workers have been asked to
chlorinate water sources in villages and small towns across the state, he
said. Nearly 70 per cent of the state's 165 million people lack access to
safe drinking water. Rains cause water-logging in areas lacking proper
drainage systems and contaminate water in ponds and wells used by villagers
for drinking. More than 200 people died of diarrhea, cholera and malaria in
the state during the last monsoon season.
[byline: Correspondents in Lucknow, India]
[Although the etioilogy or etiologies of the diarrheal illnesses is not
stated, it is probable that some of the cases are cholera based on
mortality reports. - Mod.LL]
